msIdentifier.idno: Cambridge, Fitzwilliam Museum, MS Charles Fairfax Murray 30

summary.seg: Probably copied in Italy in the 15th century, this copy of the Gospel of John was bound together towards the end of that century with a variety of other materials. These include a printed edition of the medical text De natura hominis by Hippocrates, translated in 1479-1480 by the Paduan humanist Andrea Brenta (c. 1454-c. 1485) and published in Rome around 1492, supplemented by related letters between Brenta and his correspondents. There is also a series of texts in Latin, including letters of the condottiere Alessandro Sforza (1409-1473), poems, medical and magical recipes and instructions for other chemical procedures such as making gunpowder, and a Latin translation of the pseudo-Aristotelian text the Secretum secretorum, in the 13th-century Latin translation of Philip of Tripoli.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers i-iii + iv-vi + 1-109 + vii-viii, in pencil, in Arabic and Roman numerals, recto, upper right.
supportDesc.condition: There is some water staining, mould staining and areas of dirt.

binding.p: Late 15th-century Italian full leather binding over wooden boards. Supported sewing with alum tawed skin supports. Traces of cord suggest that the book may have been resewn on cord and the previous supports kept on the spine. Both boards and the spine are decorated with blind tooling. Board attachment may be by laced-in slips. There are plain pastedowns and separate sewn endleaves of a later date. The metal catchplate of a fastening survives on the right boards, with a small remnant of the strap on the left board.
binding.condition: There is cracking to the leather covering of the spine.

physDesc.accMat: On the left pastedown is a printed note reading From the library of Charles Fairfax Murray and a printed and handwritten note of donation by Murray in 1905.

history.origin: The various portions of the volume were probably bound together in the late 15th century in Italy, as suggested by the style of the binding. This must have occurred after about 1492, the date of publication of Brenta's translation of De natura hominis.
history.provenance: Owned by the painter and collector Charles Fairfax Murray (1848-1919) Murray, Charles Fairfax, 1849-1919 .
history.acquisition: Given to the Fitzwilliam Museum by Murray in 1905.

support.material: Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermark: Unidentified motif ( c. 45 29 ) in the gutter.

collation.p: This part consists of a single folio, a quinion.

handNote.p: The text of ff. 1r-10v was copied by Hand A in mixed minuscule script, slanting to the right, in black ink, with modest variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear only at the end of lines. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is occasional decorative use of the double dot. Nomina sacra are accentuated only when more than three letters long.
The modern eta, modern nu and sigma telikon are present.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower comma, question mark and full stop.

decoDesc.decoNote: The text on f. 1r begins with a minor initial in bright red ink.
The beginning of the text on f. 1r is preceded by a vignette in red ink.

history.origin: This portion of the manuscript was probably copied in the 15th century in Italy, as suggested by the style of script.
